Approaching the Central Question

My central question revolves around which of the three basketball players in the dataset is the greatest basketball player of all time. To approach this question, Iâve decided to evaluate it by who would have won the MVP the most times between the three individuals. Iâm restricting the timeframe to the first fifteen seasons of each playerâs respective career. This was decided to limit out the longevity arguments for players that have had longer careers than others. Now, I understand that the Most Valuable Player in the NBA is often based on a playerâs merit as well as team success. To assign the MVP to one of these three players in their first fifteen seasons, I have come up with my own metric score for evaluation.

The MVP will be a much more statistically based award. This is because I will be using a variety of stats reflecting a playerâs true impact over every single minute played during a season. To measure offensive output, I am including points, assists, and rebounds. For defensive output, I am additionally using steals and blocks. The specific Score for each player in a given season will be calculated by:

Score = (Points + Assists + Rebounds + Steals + Blocks) / Minutes Played

Once this score is calculated for each game played in a given season for a player, the average of all the scores in a season will be computed as a final reflection to compare. The greatest final mean score, each season, will justify who shouldâve won the MVP. Then, I plan to add up MVPs for each player and deduce which player is the most valuable the most number of seasons. I believe that this analysis justifies who was the greatest NBA player from the first fifteen seasons of their respective careers.
